Proposed Definition of Done – CI/CD Orchestration (Common Standard)

For any user story, task, or feature to be considered Done, the following criteria must be met:
✅ 1. Functional Completion

    Business and technical requirements are fully implemented.

    Story acceptance criteria are met and verified by the Product Owner.

    All functional testing is complete (unit, integration, system).

✅ 2. Documentation & Traceability

    All required documentation (e.g., implementation notes, changes made, impacted systems) is updated.

    Relevant records are stored in the correct repository (e.g., Confluence, SharePoint, or system of record).

    Jira ticket is updated with final status, comments, and references to any linked tasks, exceptions, or approvals.

✅ 3. Security, Risk, and Compliance Checks

    Security review is completed if required (based on classification or impact).

    Policy Exceptions (PEs) or Deferred Remediation Dates (DRDs) are submitted and linked if full compliance cannot be achieved.

    Patch compliance (if applicable) is validated or exemption tracked.

    Any control-related evidence (e.g., audit readiness) is captured and stored.

✅ 4. Stakeholder Communication

    Relevant stakeholders (Product Owner, requestors, downstream consumers) have been notified of completion.

    Status has been reflected in any required dashboards or status reports (if part of KR1/KR3 deliverables).

✅ 5. Integration and Deployment

    Code or configuration is merged, built, and deployed to the appropriate environment(s).

    Automated CI/CD pipelines have run successfully.

    Rollback steps are documented if required.

✅ 6. Validation & Post-Completion

    Validated in production or designated test environment (if post-release validation is applicable).

    Any known limitations or future enhancements are captured in backlog.

    Story is ready for audit review (where applicable) with supporting artifacts attached or linked.
